The role of active species in the photocatalytic degradation were examined with the help of various scavengers the observed results were shown in Fig. 5 (a). The IPA, EDTA and BQ were used to trap hydroxyl radicals (OH
), holes (h) and superoxide radicals (
O2 –) respectively. In Fig. 5(a) a drastic decrease in the photocatalytic activity after the addition of a BQ and IPA shows that the superoxide radicals (
O2 –) and hydroxyl radicals (OH
) radicals are the main active species in the photocatalytic degradation. The recycle test was conducted under similar photocatalytic reaction conditions and every cycle the photocatalyst was collected, centrifuged and washed with ethanol and double-distilled water. Then the obtained photocatalysts particles were dried in a hot air oven for overnight. Up to five cycles of degradation, there were no significant changes in degradation efficiency. As shown by the degradation efficiency of the prepared samples, the catalyst particles are durable and recyclable (Fig. 5(b).
